{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526984"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:28:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:28:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14187"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583967"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:33:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:33:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14187"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14187"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.26,0.01,0.57,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105821"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6870"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2024-09-16T22:14:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T15:57:10+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-09-16T22:27:03+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 21:26:15"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14187"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88290"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1514"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43501"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88290"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105821"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of dysuria and urinary frequency. She has no fever or flank pain. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her regular medications include metformin, lisinopril, and amlodipine. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Urinalysis is positive for leukocytes and nitrites. She is diagnosed with uncomplicated cystitis and prescribe trimethoprim. Two weeks later, she returns for a follow-up. Her urinary symptoms have resolved, but routine blood tests reveal the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 5.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 120 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 49 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for these laboratory findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dehydration from increased urinary frequency","Acute kidney injury due to urinary tract infection","Undiagnosed primary hyperaldosteronism","Drug-induced hyperkalaemia and creatinine elevation","Progression of underlying diabetic nephropathy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely explanation for this patient\u0027s laboratory findings is \u003Cstrong\u003Edrug-induced hyperkalaemia and creatinine elevation\u003C/strong\u003E (due to the inhibition of tubular secretion of creatinine rather than reflecting a true decrease in glomerular filtration rate) caused by trimethoprim.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgression of underlying diabetic nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to cause such rapid changes in renal function and potassium levels over just two weeks. While diabetic nephropathy is a concern in patients with long-standing diabetes, it typically progresses more slowly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute kidney injury due to urinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E is not likely in this case. The patient\u0027s symptoms had resolved, and uncomplicated cystitis rarely causes significant kidney injury. Moreover, the potassium rise is not proportional to the rise in creatinine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDehydration from increased urinary frequency\u003C/strong\u003E is not likely in this case. The patient\u0027s symptoms had resolved, and dehydration severe enough to cause this degree of renal impairment would likely present with other clinical signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUndiagnosed primary hyperaldosteronism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with hypokalaemia, not hyperkalaemia, making this an unlikely explanation for the patient\u0027s current lab results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trimethoprim can cause hyperkalaemia, particularly in elderly patients or those with renal impairment.","Trimethoprim can interfere with creatinine secretion, leading to a transient rise in serum creatinine rather than reflecting a genuine decline in glomerular filtration."],"references":["Kennard A, Roberts DM. Trimethoprim-induced critical hyperkalaemia. In: Australian Prescriber [online]. 2016. Available at: https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/trimethoprim-induced-critical-hyperkalaemia.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88290"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14187"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88290"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:51:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T09:51:42+09:30","number":8,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6870"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105821"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"